Indonesia Stocks: Asuransi Harta, Bank Negara, Bayan Resources

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a   a n d   G r e g   A h l s t r a n d
-- 
2011-06-07T09:44:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-07/indonesia-stocks-bank-negara-indonesia-bayan-resources-energi.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 4 p.m. Jakarta-time close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  gained 8.75 points, or 0.2
percent, to 3,842.95.  Palm oil producers: PT Perusahaan Perkebunan London Sumatra
 Indonesia  (LSIP IJ), the nation’s third-largest listed
plantation company by market value, dropped 1 percent to 2,400
rupiah. PT Astra Agro Lestari (AALI IJ), the biggest, fell 0.4
percent to 23,500 rupiah. Palm oil futures in  Kuala Lumpur 
declined for a second day, losing as much as 1.3 percent.  PT Asuransi Harta Aman Pratama (AHAP IJ) surged 34 percent
to 215 rupiah, the steepest increase since Jan. 26, 2004. The
insurance company plans to merge with a local rival and sell new
shares to strengthen capital, Kontan reported today. Asuransi
Harta Corporate Secretary Sutjianta couldn’t be reached when
called at his office.  PT  Bank Negara  Indonesia (BBNI IJ), Indonesia’s third-
largest state-owned bank, rose 1.3 percent to 3,825 rupiah. The
bank obtained a $50 million, two-year loan from Wells Fargo Bank
NA to strengthen foreign-exchange liquidity and to improve the
composition of its short-term and long-term funding, it said.  PT Bayan Resources (BYAN IJ), an Indonesian coal producer,
gained 2.4 percent to 19,000 rupiah, the highest close since its
August 2008 trading debut. The company said it obtained a $185
million  bank loan  to help fund the acquisition of nine companies
with mining concessions in Indonesia’s East Kalimantan province.  To contact the reporter on this story:
